econet-eth: WHNAT vif registry (F1) -- map mt76 AP netdevs to PPE vif index

WiFi HW-NAT half-offload, phase 1. The OEM WHNAT scheme tags each AP
pseudo-interface with a VirIfIdx so the PPE's force-to-CPU downstream frames
can be muxed back to the right BSS on egress. This adds the econet-eth side
of that map: a small array (en75_wifi_vif[16] = OEM HWNAT_WLAN_IF_MAXNUM)
keyed by the mt76 mvif->idx, plus register/lookup helpers modelled on the OEM
ppe_dev_register_hook()/DstPort[] table.

  en75_whnat_register_vif(dev, idx) / _unregister_vif(idx) -- EXPORT_SYMBOL,
      called by mt76 from mt7603_add/remove_interface (next patch, weak refs).
  en75_whnat_vif_by_idx(idx) -- idx -> netdev with an extra hold (the F3 demux
      dev_put()s after dev_queue_xmit; closes the unregister-vs-xmit race).
  en75_whnat_idx_by_dev(dev) / _idx_by_mac(mac) -- reverse lookups for F2
      (en75_flow_offload_replace spots a WiFi egress flow by its smac, which
      equals the AP vif's dev_addr -- verified on HW, cont32t).
  en75_whnat_flush_vifs() -- drop all holds on module exit (no netdev leak if
      mt76 is still loaded), wired into en75_remove().

The array holds a netdev reference while a vif is registered so the stored
pointer stays valid for the NAPI reader. No datapath change yet: nothing calls
the lookups until F2/F3, so this patch is inert on its own.

